st}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|S\u00e9bastien Buemi}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.buemi.ch}}\n* {{DriverDB driver|sebastien-buemi}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of FIA World Endurance champions|World Endurance Drivers Champion]]|before= [[Tom Kristensen (racing driver)|Tom Kristensen]]<br/>[[Allan McNish]]<br/>[[Lo\u00efc Duval]] |after=[[Timo Bernhard]]<br/>[[Brendon Hartley]]<br/>[[Mark Webber]]|years= [[2014 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2014]]|with=[[Anthony Davidson]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Nelson Piquet Jr.]]|title=[[FIA Formula E Championship|Formula E Champion]]|years=[[2015-16 Formula E season|2015-16]]|after=[[Lucas di Grassi]]}}\n{{succession box|title= [[List of 24 Hours of Le Mans winners|Winner of the 24 Hours of Le Mans]]|before= [[Timo Bernhard]]<br/>[[Brendon Hartley]]<br/>[[Earl Bamber]] |after=Incumbent|years= [[2018 24 Hours of Le Mans|2018]]<br/>[[2019 24 Hours of Le Mans|2019]]|with=[[Fernando Alonso]] & [[Kazuki Nakajima]]}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[List of FIA World Endurance champions|World Endurance Drivers Champion]] |before= [[Timo Bernhard]]<br/>[[Brendon Hartley]]<br/>[[Earl Bamber]]|after= Incumbent|years=[[2018\u201319 FIA World Endurance Championship|2018\u201319]]|with=[[Fernando Alonso]] & [[Kazuki Nakajima]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{E.dams Formula E}}\n{{FIA World Endurance Championship champions}}\n{{Formula E teams}}\n{{24 Hours of Le Mans winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buemi, Sebastien}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Aigle]]\n[[Category:Swiss-French people]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriates in Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss racing drivers]]\n[[Category:People of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:People of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Formula Renault 2.0 NEC drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula Renault Eurocup drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula BMW ADAC drivers]]\n[[Category:A1 Team Switzerland drivers]]\n[[Category:GP2 Asia Series drivers]]\n[[Category:GP2 Series drivers]]\n[[Category:Swiss Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Toro Rosso Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans winning drivers]]\n[[Category:FIA World Endurance Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula E drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula E Champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Swiss racing driver}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name = S\u00e9bastien Buemi\n| image = \u00d6AMTC Welt des Motorsports 2016-80.jpg\n| caption = Buemi in 2016\n| nationality = {{flagicon|SUI}} Swiss\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|10|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Aigle]], Switzerland\n| related to = [[Natacha Gachnang]] (cousin)\n|current series = [[FIA World Endurance Championship]]\n|first year = [[2012 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2012]]\n|current team = [[Toyota Motorsport GmbH|Toyota Gazoo Racing]]\n|car number = 8\n|former teams =\n|starts = 56\n|championships = 2 ([[2014 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2014]]), ([[2018\u201319 FIA World Endurance Championship|2018\u201319]])\n|wins = 16\n|poles = 7\n|fastest laps = 7\n|best finish = 1st\n|year = [[2014 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2014]]\n|module =\n{{Infobox racing driver|embed=yes\n|current series= [[FIA Formula E Championship|Formula E]]\n|first year=[[2014\u201315 Formula E season|2014\u201315]]\n|current team= [[DAMS|Nissan e.dams]]\n|car number= 23\n|former teams= 0\n|starts= 61\n|wins= 13\n|podiums= 26\n|championships= 1\n|poles= 14\n|fastest laps= 7\n|best finish= 1st\n|year= [[2015\u201316 Formula E season|2015\u201316]]\n}}\n{{Infobox F1 driver|embed=yes\n| Years = {{f1|2009}}\u2013{{f1|2011}}\n| Teams = [[Scuderia Toro Rosso|Toro Rosso]]\n| Races = 55 (55 starts)\n| Championships = 0\n| Wins = 0\n| Podiums = 0\n| Points = 29\n| Poles = 0\n| Fastest laps = 0\n| First race = [[2009 Australian Grand Prix]]\n| Last race = [[2011 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n| Last season = \n| Last position = \n}}\n{{Infobox Le Mans driver | embed=yes\n| Years = {{24hLM|2012}}\u2013\n| Team(s) = [[Toyota Motorsport GmbH|Toyota Racing]]\n| Best Finish = 1st ({{24hLM|2018}}), ({{24hLM|2019}})\n| Class Wins = 2\n}}\n}}\n'''S\u00e9bastien Olivier Buemi''' (born 31 October 1988)<ref name=thm>{{cite web|title= FIA World Endurance Championship Team&nbsp;\u2013 S\u00e9bastien Buemi (#8) |url= http://www.toyotahybridracing.com/team/drivers/sebastien-buemi-8/ |work= Toyota Racing |accessdate= 27 May 2012 }}</ref> is a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] professional racing driver, who competes in the [[FIA Formula E Championship]] for [[DAMS|Nissan e.dams]]. He competed for [[Scuderia Toro Rosso]] in [[Formula One]]. As of 2019, Buemi is a reserve driver for Scuderia Toro Rosso's sister team, [[Red Bull Racing]].\n\nBuemi has competed in the [[FIA World Endurance Championship]] with [[Toyota Motorsport GmbH|Toyota Gazoo Racing]] (formerly Toyota Racing) since 2012. He became the [[2014 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2014]] [[List of FIA World Endurance champions|World Endurance Champion]] in the LMP1 class.<ref name=\"WEC Champions\">{{cite magazine|last=Watkins|first=Gary|date=15 November 2014|title=Davidson and Buemi champions as sister Toyota wins|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/116785|magazine=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> He won both the [[2018 24 Hours of Le Mans]] and, subsequently, the [[2018\u201319 FIA World Endurance Championship|2018-19 WEC Championship]].\n\nBuemi has raced [[FIA Formula E Championship]] with [[DAMS|e.dams Renault]] (now known as [[Nissan e.dams]]) since 2014. He won the Formula E Championship in 2015-16.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Formula BMW===\nBorn in [[Aigle]], [[Vaud]], Buemi graduated from [[Kart racing|karting]] and spent 2004 and 2005 in German [[Formula BMW]], finishing third and second in the championship respectively. He was also runner up in the 2005 FBMW World Final.\n\n===Formula Three===\nFollowing a single race in Spanish [[Formula Three]] in 2005, Buemi moved up to the [[Formula Three Euroseries]] for 2006, finishing 12th in the championship, ceding 11th place to [[Charlie Kimball]] on countback. He remained in the series for 2007, and finished second in the championship, behind [[Romain Grosjean]]. He has also competed in the special [[Masters of Formula 3]] and [[Macau Grand Prix]] races.\n\n===A1 Grand Prix===\nFor the [[2006\u201307 A1 Grand Prix season]], Buemi shared driving duties for [[A1 Team Switzerland]] with [[Neel Jani]] and [[Marcel F\u00e4ssler (racing driver)|Marcel F\u00e4ssler]]. The team finished eighth in the championship.\n\n===GP2 Series===\n\n[[File:Sebastien Buemi 2008 GP2 Silverstone.jpg|thumb|right|Buemi driving for [[Arden International]] at the [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]] round of the [[2008 GP2 Series season]]]]\n\nBuemi was drafted in at short notice to replace the injured [[Michael Ammerm\u00fcller]] at [[ART Grand Prix]] for the [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] round of the [[2007 GP2 Series season]]. He performed creditably on his [[GP2 Series|GP2]] d\u00e9but, qualifying fourth and finishing seventh. He joined the [[Arden International]] team for the [[2008 GP2 Asia Series season|2008 GP2 Asia Series]], and finished as runner-up with a win and four second places. He continued with the team for the main [[2008 GP2 Series season|2008 season]].<ref>{{cite news| title =Arden target return to form in 2008 | publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/64616| date =2007-01-10| accessdate =2007-01-13}}</ref> He scored his first win in the French sprint race, starting 21st on the grid (after a technical problem in the feature race) on slick tyres on a drying track and benefitting as most rivals had to pit for slicks.  He won one more race and ended the season sixth in the championship.\n\n===Formula One===\nOn 18 September 2007 he drove the [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]] [[Red Bull RB3|RB3]] at the F1 test session in [[Circuito de Jerez|Jerez]]. He was third quickest on the day, behind [[Timo Glock]] ([[BMW Sauber|BMW]]) and [[Vitantonio Liuzzi]] ([[Scuderia Toro Rosso]]) but ahead of names such as [[Rubens Barrichello]] ([[Honda F1|Honda]]) and Nelson Piquet Jr. ([[Renault F1|Renault]]). On 16 January 2008 Red Bull Racing confirmed Buemi as their test and reserve driver for the [[2008 Formula One season|2008 season]].<ref name=\"S\u00e9bastien Buemi confirmed as Red Bull reserve\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/64709 | title = Buemi confirmed as Red Bull reserve | magazine = Autosport |date=2008-01-16 | accessdate = 2008-01-16}}</ref> At the [[2008 Japanese Grand Prix]], Buemi drove the medical car as usual driver Dr Jacques Tropenat had been suffering from an ear problem.<ref name=\"Buemi Japan\">{{cite magazine |date=October 2008 |title=Buemi's F1 \"race\" debut |magazine=[[Autosport]] |volume=194 |issue=3 |page=15 }}</ref>\n\n====Scuderia Toro Rosso (2009\u20132011)====\n\n=====2009=====\n[[File:Tororosso-buemi6-spain-2009-lrg.jpg|thumb|right|Buemi during free practice at the [[2009 Spanish Grand Prix]].]]\n[[Scuderia Toro Rosso]] confirmed its signing of Buemi as one of its race drivers on 9 January 2009.<ref name=\"Buemi\">{{cite news | url = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/72695 | title = Toro Rosso confirm Buemi for 2009 | publisher = autosport.com |date=2009-01-09 | accessdate = 2009-01-09}}</ref> He was the first Swiss driver to take part in an F1 race since [[Jean-Denis D\u00e9l\u00e9traz]] drove for [[Pacific Racing|Pacific]] at the [[1995 European Grand Prix]].\n\nIn his first race, the [[2009 Australian Grand Prix]], Buemi outqualified his teammate [[S\u00e9bastien Bourdais]] and then scored a point in the race by finishing in eighth position. He was later promoted to seventh place as a result of [[Lewis Hamilton]] being disqualified. At the [[2009 Chinese Grand Prix|Chinese Grand Prix]], he scored another point, this time in the wet, finishing eighth after starting tenth. After a mid season dip in the Toro Rosso's form, Buemi rounded off a good weekend to finish 7th in the [[2009 Brazilian Grand Prix]]. He followed this with a third top ten qualification in a row and another points finish at the season finale in [[2009 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix|Abu Dhabi]]. Buemi finished the year sixteenth with 6 points as the best rookie.\n\n=====2010=====\n[[File:Buemi spain 2010.JPG|thumb|left|Buemi driving the Toro Rosso STR5 during practice for the [[2010 Spanish Grand Prix]]]]\nOn 9 November 2009, it was confirmed that Buemi would race for a second season with Toro Rosso.\n\nDuring the first free practice session of the [[2010 Chinese Grand Prix]], a front [[Double wishbone suspension|suspension]] wishbone broke under braking on Buemi's Toro Rosso as he braked for Turn 14. The two front wheels flew off while Buemi was travelling at over {{convert|300|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. One wheel went over the safety fence and landed in a spectator area, missing a camera man on its way. Buemi's car continued to travel forward, veering to the left and sliding along an [[Armco barrier]], knocking off the front wing. Neither Buemi nor any spectators were injured as a result of the incident. Toro Rosso blamed a failure of a new front right upright for the incident.<ref>{{cite news|last=Noble|first=Jonathan|title=Upright failure caused Buemi's crash|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|work=autosport.com|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/82899|date=2010-04-16|accessdate=2010-04-16}}</ref> Buemi completed 2010 with eight points to teammate Alguersuari's five. He was sixteenth again in the drivers' championship.\n\n=====2011=====\n[[File:S Buemi 2 Monza 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Buemi driving for Toro Rosso at the [[2011 Italian Grand Prix]]]]\nBuemi, along with his teammate from 2009 and 2010&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jaime Alguersuari]], continued to race for Scuderia Toro Rosso in 2011.\nOn 14 December 2011 it was announced that both Buemi and Alguersuari had been dropped by the team, and would be replaced by [[Daniel Ricciardo]] and [[Jean-\u00c9ric Vergne]] for the {{F1|2012}} season.\n\n====Red Bull Racing (2012-present)====\n\n=====2012=====\nIn January 2012 it was announced that Buemi would rejoin [[Red Bull Racing]] as a test and reserve driver for the {{F1|2012}} season, as well as acting as Toro Rosso's reserve driver.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Sebastien Buemi confirmed as Red Bull Racing's reserve and test driver|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/96889|first=Pablo|last=Elizalde|magazine=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\nBuemi continued as [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]]'s test and reserve driver for the {{F1|2013}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Sebastien Buemi will continue as Red Bull's test and reserve driver for the 2013 season|url=http://www1.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/8422512/|accessdate=6 December 2013|newspaper=SkySports F1}}</ref> and {{F1|2014}} seasons.\nBuemi was again announced as reserve driver for 2019 for [[Red Bull Racing]].\n\n===Sportscars===\n[[File:Toyota TS040 Hybrid at Le Mans 2014 003.jpg|thumb|The [[Toyota TS040 Hybrid]] that Buemi drove at the [[2014 24 Hours of Le Mans]].]]\nBuemi also signed a deal to contest the [[2012 24 Hours of Le Mans|24 Hours of Le Mans]] with [[Toyota Motorsport GmbH]], driving a [[Toyota TS030 Hybrid]] with [[Anthony Davidson]] and [[Hiroaki Ishiura]] (who later withdrew and was replaced by [[St\u00e9phane Sarrazin]]).<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Toyota recruits Anthony Davidson, Sebastien Buemi for second TS030 HYBRID|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/97474|magazine=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> After a strong performance, the car was running in third position in the early evening when Davidson collided with a GT Ferrari and crashed heavily.\n\nIn [[2013 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2013]], Buemi continued driving with Toyota for a full season and ended with third place in the drivers' championship. For the [[2014 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2014 season]], he drove Toyota's new car&nbsp;\u2013 the [[Toyota TS040 Hybrid]]. With four wins and seven podiums from the eight races, Buemi became World Endurance Drivers' Champion with teammate [[Anthony Davidson]].<ref name=\"WEC Champions\"/>\n\n===Formula E (2014\u2013present)===\n\nBuemi is currently the most successful driver in the series' history having claimed more wins, poles, fastest laps and points than any other driver in the series.\n\n====Renault e.dams (2014\u20132018)====\n\nBuemi raced in the [[2014\u201315 Formula E season|inaugural Formula E season]] for [[DAMS|e.dams]] alongside Frenchman [[Nicolas Prost]].\n\n====2014\u201315====\n\nBuemi's season did not start off easily with a retirement in [[2014 Beijing ePrix|Beijing]] having started from last on the grid and being unable to set a qualifying time at the following round in [[2014 Putrajaya ePrix|Putrajaya]], he lined up 19th on the grid. Buemi drove a brilliant recovery race having started in 19th and finishing 3rd on the podium ahead of his teammate who started in 11th. At the third round of the season Buemi secured his first race victory in [[2014 Punta del Este ePrix|Punta del Este]]. Buemi started on pole at the following round in [[2015 Buenos Aires ePrix|Buenos Aires]] for the first time in his career but crashed out of the race after leading. Buemi went on to win in [[2015 Monaco ePrix|Monaco]] and the [[2015 London ePrix|first London race]], both from pole position, whereas he finished second in [[2015 Berlin ePrix|Berlin]].  Buemi finished the season second in the championship, one point short of Nelson Piquet Jr.'s tally.\n\n====2015\u201316====\n[[File:2015 Punta del Este ePrix - Race - 19.JPG|thumbnail|right|Buemi at the [[2015 Punta del Este ePrix]].]]\nIn season two, Buemi dominated the early stages of the championship.  In the season opening round in [[2015 Beijing ePrix|Beijing]] Buemi secured pole, fastest lap and the race win.  The story was looking much the same in the following round in [[2015 Putrajaya ePrix|Putrajaya]] before Buemi's car experienced mechanical failure while leading the race.  Having made a mistake in qualifying in [[2015 Punta del Este ePrix|Punta del Este]], Buemi lined up fifth on the grid, but went on to claim his third fastest lap in three races and another race victory. Next he finished second in [[2016 Buenos Aires ePrix|Buenos Aires]] and [[2016 Mexico City ePrix|Mexico]].\n\nAfter a third-place finish at Paris, Buemi scored his third win of the season at [[2016 Berlin ePrix|Berlin]], setting up a nail bitting finale in [[2016 London ePrix|London]]. With Buemi needing to finish ahead of rival [[Lucas di Grassi]] to win the championship in the second race of the weekend, he was hit off by no other than Di Grassi himself at the first corner. Therefore, the title was to be headed to whoever could get the fastest lap bonus points in their second car. Despite the immense pressure, Buemi cruised to the fastest lap to become Formula E champion 2015-16.\n\n====2016\u201317====\n\nSeason three started exceptionally well for Buemi, as he won the first three rounds of the [[2016-17 Formula E season|championship]], becoming the first Formula E driver to achieve the feat of three consecutive wins. Buemi would go on to take three more wins at [[2017 Monaco ePrix|Monaco]],<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Sebastien Buemi wins intense Formula E Monaco ePrix|url=http://autoweek.com/article/other-motorsports/sebastien-buemi-wins-intense-formula-e-monaco-eprix|magazine=[[Autoweek]]|publisher=[[Crain Communications|Crain Communications, Inc.]]|date=13 May 2017|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> [[2017 Paris ePrix|Paris]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Another win for Buemi in Paris Formula E race|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-motor-electric-france-idUSKCN18G0V1|work=[[Reuters|Reuters.com]]|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> and [[2017 Berlin ePrix|Berlin]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=S\u00e9bastien Buemi wins Formula E race in Berlin|url=http://autoweek.com/article/other-motorsports/sebastien-buemi-wins-formula-e-race-berlin-0|magazine=[[Autoweek]]|publisher=[[Crain Communications|Crain Communications, Inc.]]|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> before the final 4 races in [[2017 New York ePrix|New York City]] and [[2017 Montreal ePrix|Montreal]], both double headers.\n\nHowever, Buemi skipped the New York event due to his [[2017 FIA World Endurance Championship season|WEC]] commitments with Toyota and participated in the [[2017 6 Hours of N\u00fcrburgring|6 Hours of N\u00fcrburgring]] instead, with [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]] F1 test and reserve driver [[Pierre Gasly]] taking his place.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Gasly favourite to replace Buemi for New York ePrix|url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/gasly-favourite-to-replace-buemi-for-new-york-eprix-921249/|magazine=[[Motorsport.com]]|publisher=[[Motorsport.com|Motorsport Network]]|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> In addition, he was disqualified from two races for technical infringements. Ultimately, this loss of points led to Buemi missing out on the championship as rival [[Lucas di Grassi]] took the title at the final race.\n\n====2017\u201318====\n\nBuemi endured a tough start to the season, taking only one point from the opening double-header at [[2017 Hong Kong ePrix|Hong Kong]], having been involved in some incidents, including with previous seasons' title rival Lucas di Grassi. Buemi hit back with pole position at [[2018 Marrakesh ePrix|Marrakesh]]. He led the race throughout, until 4 laps from the end, he was passed by the Mahindra of [[Felix Rosenqvist]]. He achieved two podium finishes at the next two races, to leave him in 4th place in the standings. However, he crashed out of the following race in [[2018 Punta del Este ePrix|Punta del Este]]. His Renault e.dams, however, proved not to be as competitive as previous seasons, and while consistently scoring in the points, he did not achieve a race win or podium for the next 4 races. In the final ePrix of the season, a double-header at [[2018 New York City ePrix|New York]], Buemi qualified on pole in both rounds, with the final round being achieved in the first wet qualifying session in Formula E history. However, he would slip behind faster cars in the races to 3rd and 4th respectively. This meant he finished the season in 4th place, his lowest position in the standings since Formula E began, with 125 points. Renault e.dams finished the season 5th in the standings, the first time they had not won the Teams' Championship, with Buemi scoring 125 out of the team's 133 points.\n\n====Nissan e.dams (2018\u2013present)====\n\nIt was announced that the [[DAMS]] would switch from Renault to Nissan from the [[2018-19 Formula E season|2018-19]] season. Buemi was initially meant to partner [[Alexander Albon]], who raced for the DAMS Formula 2 team, but he was released by DAMS to join Buemi's former team, [[Scuderia Toro Rosso|Toro Rosso]] to race in F1 in [[2019 Formula One World Championship|2019]]. Albon was replaced by [[Oliver Rowland]], who had previously raced for DAMS in Formula 2 in 2017.\n\n====2018\u201319====\n\nBuemi started the season with 3rd place on the grid, but slipped to 6th by the end of the race. At the next round in [[2019 Marrakesh ePrix|Marrakesh]], Buemi again started 3rd on the grid, but had to avoid the spinning Techeetah of [[Jean-\u00c9ric Vergne]] and fell down the order. However, by the end of the race, he recovered to 8th place. At the next race, in [[2019 Santiago ePrix|Santiago]], he inherited pole position when Lucas di Grassi was disqualified for a technical infringement. However, he crashed out of lead towards the end of the race due to a brake failure. Buemi's misfortune continued, when at the next race, both he and his teammate Rowland ran out of energy a lap before the end of the race, running in 4th and 3rd respectively, after Nissan had miscalculated the number of laps remaining. This was followed by a suspension failure causing him to retire from the following round. At the next round he crashed during his superpole run and therefore qualified 6th, but he was later disqualified for a technical infringement and had to start from the pit lane. By the last lap, he had made his way up to 8th place, but while attempting to overtake [[Robin Frijns]], Buemi ploughed into the back of him, causing Frijns to take out di Grassi, moving Buemi up to 6th, while di Grassi retired on the spot, and Frijns limped back home in 14th. Buemi was given a 10-second time penalty for causing the collision and was classified 8th, the position he was in before the crash. He also had trouble in [[2019 Rome ePrix|Rome]] and [[2019 Paris ePrix|Paris]]. However, after taking pole for the [[2019 Berlin ePrix|Berlin ePrix]], his results improved. He finished second, after di Grassi overtook him and won the race. In [[2019 Swiss ePrix|Bern]], and in Race 2 in [[2019 New York City ePrix|New York]], he finished third. His first victory of the season came in Race 1 in [[2019 New York City ePrix|New York]], after taking pole position. He was under attack from [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]] driver [[Alex Lynn]]. However, the Brit retired due to a loss of power. After that, Buemi held a comfortable margin to win the race over Lynn\u2019s teammate, [[Mitch Evans]], who had an incredible comeback from 13th position on the grid. By the end of the season, Buemi had overtaken 11 drivers, including title contenders Evans and di Grassi, to climb from 13th to 2nd in the championship.\n\n==Personal life==\nAs of 2009 Buemi was officially resident in [[Bahrain]], living with his family and his girlfriend Jennifer.<ref>[http://www.auto123.com/en/racing-news/other/f1-sebastien-buemi-to-stay-in-tax-free-bahrain?artid=104353 \"S\u00e9bastien Buemi to stay in tax-free Bahrain\"] Auto123.com 2009-01-16. Retrieved 2009-04-25.</ref> He has since moved to [[Monaco]].<ref name=\"thm\"/> His cousin, [[Natacha Gachnang]], is also a racing driver. In February 2016, Buemi became a father with the birth of his son Jules. He welcomed the birth of his second son Theo in January 2018.\n\nIn 2013, Buemi and [[Johnny Herbert]] mentored 6 contestants in a primetime [[ITV4]] [[reality series]], with the aim of taking players of the ''[[Gran Turismo (series)|Gran Turismo]]'' videogames to the [[Dubai 24 Hour]] race as real drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.touchline.tv/gaming/gran-turismo-academy-series-confirmed-for-itv4 |title=Gran Turismo Academy series confirmed for ITV4 |website=www.touchline.tv |date=January 10, 2013 |access-date=November 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213154336/http://www.touchline.tv/gaming/gran-turismo-academy-series-confirmed-for-itv4 |archive-date=February 13, 2013 }}</ref> Other countries in Europe had heats mentored by [[Vitantonio Liuzzi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu.gran-turismo.com/ie/news/d50120.html |title=GT Academy 2012 European Race Camp Gets Underway |date=August 17, 2012 |website=eu.gran-turismo.com |access-date=November 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307021222/http://eu.gran-turismo.com/ie/news/d50120.html |archive-date=March 7, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%; text-align:center\"\n! Season\n! Series\n! Team\n! Races\n! Wins\n! Poles\n! FLaps\n! Podiums\n! Points\n! Position\n|-\n! 2004\n|align=left| [[2004 Formula BMW ADAC season|Formula BMW ADAC]]\n|align=left| Lars Kaufmann Motorspo