{"title_page": "GTL Infrastructure", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name    =GTL Infrastructure\n|type     = public company\n|traded_as={{BSE|532775}}<br>{{NSE|GTLINFRA}}\n|logo     = GTL_Infrastructure_official_logo.jpg\n|logo_size = 200px\n|key_people       = \n|foundation       = 2004<ref>[http://www.livemint.com/Companies/CyCJbr1f47LSxBm3SDM24H/GTL-Infra-stake-sale-likely-to-value-firm-at-Rs11000-crore.html GTL Infra founded in 2004]</ref>\n|location         = [[Navi Mumbai]], India \n|products         = [[Network service provider|Network Services Provider]]\n|revenue          = \n|operating_income = \n|net_income       = \n|assets           = \n|equity           = \n|num_employees    = 1075 <ref>[http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/pdf/14th-Annual-Report-2016-17-with-AGM-Notice.pdf 14th Annual Report 2016-17 with AGM Notice]</ref>\n|owner            = \n|parent           = \n|divisions        = \n|subsid           = \n|industry         = \n|services         = \n|homepage         = [http://www.gtlinfra.com GTL Infrastructure Limited]\n}}\n\n'''GTL Infrastructure Limited''' (GTL Infra). a Global Group Enterprise is India's independent telecom Tower Company. It is a pioneer in the Shared Passive Telecom Infrastructure space in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |title=India\u2019s independent telecom Tower Company |publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=17 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619234258/http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/MT_Jan15-2010.pdf |archivedate=19 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHeadquartered in Navi Mumbai, Maharashtra, India, GTL Infra has about 28,000 towers located across 22 telecom circles in India, which enables telecom service providers to offer 2G, 3G and 4G services across the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/aboutgtl.cms |title=About GTL Infrastructure |publisher=Economictimes Indiatimes |accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIncorporated in 2004, under the Founder, Chairman, Manoj G Tirodkar, GTL Infra introduced the shared Infrastructure space.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/gtl-infrastructure-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-16883.cms |title=GTL Infrastructure Ltd. |publisher=Economictimes Indiatimes |accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> For FY 2016\u201317, GTL Infra registered revenue of Rs. 2286 crores and EBIDTA of Rs. 1,122 crores.\n\nThe board of directors consists of Chairman, [[Manoj G. Tirodkar|Manoj G Tirodkar]], N. Balasubramanian, Vice Chairman and Ind. Director; Milind Naik, full Time Director and COO; Charudatta Naik Director, Dr. Anand Patkar, Independent Director; Vinod B. Agarwala, Independent Director; Vijay M. Vij, Independent Director and Sonali P. Choudhary, Director.<ref name=\"team\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |title=Home :: About us :: Management Profile |publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=14 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606034244/http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |archivedate=6 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe executive management team has Milind Naik;  Milind Bengali, COO; L. Y. Desai, CFO; Prasanna Bidnurkar, Head CDR Operations; Bhupendra Kiny, Head-Pricing & Costing; Ashutosh Chandratrey Sr. V. P. \u2013 Human Resources; R. S. Ahluwalia, President \u2013 Business Development and Eugene Valles, Vice President \u2013 Training and OD.<ref name=\"team\"/>\n\n==History==\nIn the late 1990s, the telecom sector was in India was liberalised which led to a boom in the industry. All telecom players benefited from the explosive growth and opportunities it brought up. In 2006, GTL Infra became the first company in the shared telecom space to be listed on stock exchanges (BSE & NSE).  The next year, the company came out with a rights issue of US$83.86 million. In 2010, the GTL Infra acquired 17,500 towers and 21000 tenants from Aircel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/info-tech/gtl-infrachennai-network-combined-debt-falls-to-rs-4193-cr/article9767686.ece |title=GTL Infra-Chennai Network combined debt falls to Rs. 4,193 cr |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"samana\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |title=acquisition of Aircel\u2019s 17,500 towers|publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=14 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620024814/http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Samana_Jan14-2010.pdf|archivedate=20 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFounder and Chairman, Manoj G Tirodkar had conceptualised a third party independent tower company and GTL Infra was carved out of GTL Ltd, the network services arm of Global Group in 2006.\n\n===2010 onwards===\nThe telecom industry took a serious hit in 2010, when the government cancelled 122 telecom licences owing to the 2G license case.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/supreme-court-cancels-122-telecom-licences-112020300086_1.html|title=Supreme court cancels 122 telecom licences |publisher=Business Standard |date=11 Feb 2013|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> GTL Infra too suffered with the cancellation of licences as its customers reduced because of issues faced by Aircel and Maxis and subsequent cancellation of ROFR by Aircel.\n\nIn 2011, GTL Infra completed its Corporate Debt Restructuring and in 2016-17 it has completed the first phase of Strategic Debt restructuring, which has brought down the debt of the company to a sustainable Rs. 4,841 crores.\n\n==Shareholding==\nThe number of equity shares of GTL Infra are approx. 12.12 billion. The Promoter group, GTL Limited along with Global Holding Corporation Pvt Ltd, holds approx. 14.6% of the total equity shares, whereas the banks and financial institutions hold about 63.9% of equity shares in terms of Strategic Debt Restructuring Scheme. Balance are held by public shareholders, including FIIs and corporate bodies. Indian Overseas Bank is the largest non-promoter investor in the company with 10.62% shareholding as on September 2017, filed with the stock exchanges in India.\n\n==Listing==\nThe company's equity shares are listed on the National Stock Exchange of India Limited (NSE) and the BSE Limited. The Foreign Currency Convertible Bonds are listed on Singapore Exchange Securities Trading Limited.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/markets/stock-markets/21-cos-may-default-on-fccb-commitments-sp/article3555408.ece |title=21 cos may default on FCCB commitments: S&P |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |date=21 Jun 2012|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nGTL Infra owns a blend of Urban and Rural telecom towers located in all the 22 Telecom Circles in India, which are shared by all Telecom Operators in the country. GTL Infra offers a fixed and predictable OPEX model and network up time of 99.9% for its customers by real time monitoring from its NOC (Network Operations Centre) and Operations and maintenance services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news-top-story/reliance-jio-and-gtl-infra-sign-tower-infrastructure-sharing-deal-116092000305_1.html |title=Reliance Jio and GTL Infra sign Tower Infrastructure Sharing Deal |publisher=indiainfoline.com |date=20 September 2016 |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref>\n\n==Mergers and Acquisitions==\nIn 2010, GTL Infra made acquisition of Aircel's 17,500 towers and 21000 tenants.<ref name=\"samana\"/>\n\n==Awards &Recognition==\n* GTL Infra received the Best Infrastructure Brands award from Economic Times in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/media/|title=GTL Infra received the Best Infrastructure Brands award from Economic Times in 2016 |publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=14 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619171922/http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Coverage-in-TOI.pdf|archivedate=19 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* GTL Infra received the \u2018Best Independent Infrastructure Provider\u2019 in the Telecom Operator Award 2010 by leading telecom magazine tele.net.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ghc.in/Awards/GTL-Infrastructure-voted-as-the-Best-Independent-Infrastructure-Provider.aspx/ |title=GTL Infrastructure voted as the Best Independent Infrastructure Provider|publisher=Global Endless Possibilities|date=|accessdate=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n* GTL Infra was received the 10th Greentech Environment Excellence Silver Award in 2009 by Greentech.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.in/scomi-group-bags-greentech-eco-excellence-award/ |title=Scomi Group bags Greentech eco excellence award|publisher=Construction Week Online |date=26 Oct 2009|accessdate=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gtlinfra.com/ GTL Infrastructure Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2004]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name    =GTL Infrastructure\n|type     = public company\n|traded_as={{BSE|532775}}<br>{{NSE|GTLINFRA}}\n|logo     = GTL_Infrastructure_official_logo.jpg\n|logo_size = 200px\n|key_people       = \n|foundation       = 2004<ref>[http://www.livemint.com/Companies/CyCJbr1f47LSxBm3SDM24H/GTL-Infra-stake-sale-likely-to-value-firm-at-Rs11000-crore.html GTL Infra founded in 2004]</ref>\n|location         = [[Navi Mumbai]], India \n|products         = [[Network service provider|Network Services Provider]]\n|revenue          = \n|operating_income = \n|net_income       = \n|assets           = \n|equity           = \n|num_employees    = 1075 <ref>[http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/pdf/14th-Annual-Report-2016-17-with-AGM-Notice.pdf 14th Annual Report 2016-17 with AGM Notice]</ref>\n|owner            = \n|parent           = \n|divisions        = \n|subsid           = \n|industry         = \n|services         = \n|homepage         = [http://www.gtlinfra.com GTL Infrastructure Limited]\n}}\n\n'''GTL Infrastructure Limited''' (GTL Infra). a Global Group Enterprise is India's independent telecom Tower Company. It is a pioneer in the Shared Passive Telecom Infrastructure space in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |title=India\u2019s independent telecom Tower Company |publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=17 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619234258/http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/MT_Jan15-2010.pdf |archivedate=19 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHeadquartered in Navi Mumbai, Maharashtra, India, GTL Infra has about 28,000 towers located across 22 telecom circles in India, which enables telecom service providers to offer 2G, 3G and 4G services across the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/aboutgtl.cms |title=About GTL Infrastructure |publisher=Economictimes Indiatimes |accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIncorporated in 2004, under the Founder, Chairman, Manoj G Tirodkar, GTL Infra introduced the shared Infrastructure space.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/gtl-infrastructure-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-16883.cms |title=GTL Infrastructure Ltd. |publisher=Economictimes Indiatimes |accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> For FY 2016\u201317, GTL Infra registered revenue of Rs. 2286 crores and EBIDTA of Rs. 1,122 crores.\n\nThe board of directors consists of Chairman, [[Manoj G. Tirodkar|Manoj G Tirodkar]], N. Balasubramanian, Vice Chairman and Ind. Director; Milind Naik, full Time Director and COO; Charudatta Naik Director, Dr. Anand Patkar, Independent Director; Vinod B. Agarwala, Independent Director; Vijay M. Vij, Independent Director and Sonali P. Choudhary, Director.<ref name=\"team\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |title=Home :: About us :: Management Profile |publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=14 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606034244/http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |archivedate=6 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe executive management team has Milind Naik;  Milind Bengali, COO; L. Y. Desai, CFO; Prasanna Bidnurkar, Head CDR Operations; Bhupendra Kiny, Head-Pricing & Costing; Ashutosh Chandratrey Sr. V. P. \u2013 Human Resources; R. S. Ahluwalia, President \u2013 Business Development and Eugene Valles, Vice President \u2013 Training and OD.<ref name=\"team\"/>\n\n==History==\nIn the late 90's, the telecom sector was in India was liberalised which led to a boom in the industry. All telecom players benefited from the explosive growth and opportunities it brought up. In 2006, GTL Infra became the first company in the shared telecom space to be listed on stock exchanges (BSE & NSE).  The next year, the company came out with a rights issue of US$83.86 million. In 2010, the GTL Infra acquired 17,500 towers and 21000 tenants from Aircel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/info-tech/gtl-infrachennai-network-combined-debt-falls-to-rs-4193-cr/article9767686.ece |title=GTL Infra-Chennai Network combined debt falls to Rs. 4,193 cr |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"samana\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/about-us/#_gtl-infra |title=acquisition of Aircel\u2019s 17,500 towers|publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=14 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620024814/http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Samana_Jan14-2010.pdf|archivedate=20 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFounder and Chairman, Manoj G Tirodkar had conceptualised a third party independent tower company and GTL Infra was carved out of GTL Ltd, the network services arm of Global Group in 2006.\n\n===2010 onwards===\nThe telecom industry took a serious hit in 2010, when the government cancelled 122 telecom licences owing to the 2G license case.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/supreme-court-cancels-122-telecom-licences-112020300086_1.html|title=Supreme court cancels 122 telecom licences |publisher=Business Standard |date=11 Feb 2013|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> GTL Infra too suffered with the cancellation of licences as its customers reduced because of issues faced by Aircel and Maxis and subsequent cancellation of ROFR by Aircel.\n\nIn 2011, GTL Infra completed its Corporate Debt Restructuring and in 2016-17 it has completed the first phase of Strategic Debt restructuring, which has brought down the debt of the company to a sustainable Rs. 4,841 crores.\n\n==Shareholding==\nThe number of equity shares of GTL Infra are approx. 12.12 billion. The Promoter group, GTL Limited along with Global Holding Corporation Pvt Ltd, holds approx. 14.6% of the total equity shares, whereas the banks and financial institutions hold about 63.9% of equity shares in terms of Strategic Debt Restructuring Scheme. Balance are held by public shareholders, including FIIs and corporate bodies. Indian Overseas Bank is the largest non-promoter investor in the company with 10.62% shareholding as on September 2017, filed with the stock exchanges in India.\n\n==Listing==\nThe company's equity shares are listed on the National Stock Exchange of India Limited (NSE) and the BSE Limited. The Foreign Currency Convertible Bonds are listed on Singapore Exchange Securities Trading Limited.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/markets/stock-markets/21-cos-may-default-on-fccb-commitments-sp/article3555408.ece |title=21 cos may default on FCCB commitments: S&P |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |date=21 Jun 2012|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nGTL Infra owns a blend of Urban and Rural telecom towers located in all the 22 Telecom Circles in India, which are shared by all Telecom Operators in the country. GTL Infra offers a fixed and predictable OPEX model and network up time of 99.9% for its customers by real time monitoring from its NOC (Network Operations Centre) and Operations and maintenance services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news-top-story/reliance-jio-and-gtl-infra-sign-tower-infrastructure-sharing-deal-116092000305_1.html |title=Reliance Jio and GTL Infra sign Tower Infrastructure Sharing Deal |publisher=indiainfoline.com |date=20 September 2016 |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref>\n\n==Mergers and Acquisitions==\nIn 2010, GTL Infra made acquisition of Aircel's 17,500 towers and 21000 tenants.<ref name=\"samana\"/>\n\n==Awards &Recognition==\n* GTL Infra received the Best Infrastructure Brands award from Economic Times in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtlinfra.com/media/|title=GTL Infra received the Best Infrastructure Brands award from Economic Times in 2016 |publisher=GTLinfra.com |accessdate=14 November 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619171922/http://www.gtlinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Coverage-in-TOI.pdf|archivedate=19 Jun 2017 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* GTL Infra received the \u2018Best Independent Infrastructure Provider\u2019 in the Telecom Operator Award 2010 by leading telecom magazine tele.net.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ghc.in/Awards/GTL-Infrastructure-voted-as-the-Best-Independent-Infrastructure-Provider.aspx/ |title=GTL Infrastructure voted as the Best Independent Infrastructure Provider|publisher=Global Endless Possibilities|date=|accessdate=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n* GTL Infra was received the 10th Greentech Environment Excellence Silver Award in 2009 by Greentech.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.in/scomi-group-bags-greentech-eco-excellence-award/ |title=Scomi Group bags Greentech eco excellence award|publisher=Construction Week Online |date=26 Oct 2009|accessdate=20 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gtlinfra.com/ GTL Infrastructure Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2004]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GTL_Infrastructure"}
{"title_page": "Kasper Dolberg", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kasper Dolberg\n| image = Kasper Dolberg 2016.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Dolberg in training with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 2016\n| fullname = Kasper Dolberg Rasmussen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|10|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Silkeborg]], Denmark\n| height = {{height|m=1.87}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Kasper Dolberg|url=http://www.ajax.nl/teams/ajax-1/selectie/speler/kasper-dolberg.htm|website=Ajax|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132010\n| youthclubs1 = GFG Voel\n| youthyears2 = 2010\u20132015\n| youthclubs2 = [[Silkeborg IF]]\n| youthyears3 = 2015\u20132016\n| youthclubs3 = [[Ajax Youth Academy|Ajax]]\n| currentclub = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| years1 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs1 = [[Silkeborg IF]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2015\u20132019\n| clubs2 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| caps2 = 78\n| goals2 = 33\n| years3 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps3 = 23\n| goals3 = 11\n| nationalyears1 = 2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-16 football team|Denmark U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2013\u20132014\n| nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-17 football team|Denmark U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 8\n| nationalgoals2 = 5\n| nationalyears3 = 2015\n| nationalteam3 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 8\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2016\u20132019\n| nationalteam4 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 1\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| nationalyears5 = 2016\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 15\n| nationalgoals5 = 5\n| club-update = 22:55, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 15 October 2019\n}}\n'''Kasper Dolberg Rasmussen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0\u00e6sp\u0250 \u02c8t\u028cl\u02ccp\u025b\u0250\u032f\u02c0}}; born 6 October 1997) is a Danish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Ligue 1|French]] football club [[OGC Nice|Nice]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ogcnice.com/en/news/37660/kasper-dolberg-joins-ogc-nice|title=Kasper Dolberg joins O.G.C Nice|publisher=OGC Nice|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> and the [[Denmark national football team|Denmark national team]]. Dolberg made his senior debut at [[Silkeborg IF]] in May 2015. He joined Ajax in July 2015 and made his debut for the club in July 2016. He represented Denmark at [[Denmark national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Denmark national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[Denmark national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Denmark national under-21 football team|under-21]] level before making his [[Denmark national football team|senior]] international debut in November 2016.\n\n==Club career==\n===Silkeborg IF===\nOn 17 May 2015, he made his senior debut for Silkeborg IF in a [[Danish Superliga]] game against [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]], replacing [[Adeola Lanre Runsewe]] after 63 minutes in a 2\u20130 home defeat.<ref name=\"soccerway2\">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/05/17/denmark/superliga/silkeborg-if-fs/brondby-if/1690355/|title=Silkeborg vs. Br\u00f8ndby IF - 17 May 2015 - Soccerway|publisher=soccerway.com|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Ajax===\nOn 5 January 2015, [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] announced that 17-year-old Dolberg would join from Silkeborg IF in the summer, signing a three-year contract valid from summer 2015 until summer 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ajax legt 'buitengewoon talent' Dolberg vast|trans-title=Ajax secures \"exceptional talent\" Dolberg|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajax-legt-buitengewoon-talent-dolberg-vast.htm|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Voetbal International|date=5 January 2015|language=Dutch}}</ref> He had been spotted by Danish scout John Steen Olsen, the same scout who discovered players such as [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]], [[Viktor Fischer]], and [[Christian Eriksen]] for the Dutch capital club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kijktip: Portret Deense meesterscout|url=http://www.ajax.nl/streams/ajax-actueel/kijktip-portret-deense-meesterscout.htm|website=Ajax|accessdate=5 October 2016|language=Dutch|date=12 January 2016}}</ref> On 13 May 2016, Dolberg agreed to have his contract extended until 2021.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ajax breekt contract met talent Holberg open|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajax-breekt-contract-met-talent-dolberg-open.htm|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Voetbal International|date=5 January 2015|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2016, Dolberg scored his first goal in European competition on his competitive debut for Ajax, in a 1\u20131 [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Third qualifying round|Champions League qualification]] match against [[PAOK FC|PAOK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/07/26/europe/uefa-champions-league/afc-ajax/paok-fc/2282253/|title=Ajax vs. PAOK - 26 July 2016 |publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> He made his [[Eredivisie]] debut for the club on 7 August 2016 in a match against [[Sparta Rotterdam]], coming on as a substitute for [[Mateo Cassierra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/08/07/netherlands/eredivisie/sparta-rotterdam-bv/afc-ajax/2240300/|title=Sparta Rotterdam vs. Ajax - 7 August 2016|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> The following week he was in the starting line-up for the league match against [[Roda JC]] and he scored both of Ajax' goals in the 2\u20132 draw, his first goals in the Eredivisie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/08/13/netherlands/eredivisie/afc-ajax/roda-jc/2240304/|title=Ajax vs. Roda JC - 13 August 2016|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> On 29 September 2016, Dolberg scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Standard Li\u00e8ge]] in a [[2016\u201317 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/09/29/europe/uefa-cup/afc-ajax/standard-de-liege/2348968/|title=Ajax vs. Standard Li\u00e8ge - 29 September 2016 |publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> He scored another goal in his first '[[De Klassieker|Klassieker]]' against Ajax' great rival [[Feyenoord]] on 23 October 2016, securing a 1\u20131 draw away in Rotterdam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/10/23/netherlands/eredivisie/feyenoord-rotterdam-nv/afc-ajax/2240371/|title=Feyenoord vs. Ajax - 23 October 2016|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> On 20 November 2016, he scored a first-half [[hat-trick]] in an [[Eredivisie]] match against [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Razendsnelle hattrick Dolberg|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/27069608/__Razendsnelle_hattrick_Dolberg__.html|accessdate=20 November 2016|work=[[De Telegraaf]]|date=20 November 2016|language=Dutch}}</ref> This made him the youngest non-Dutch player ever to score a hattrick for Ajax.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajax.nl/streams/wedstrijden/dolberg-verwerft-zich-plek-in-de-recordboeken-.htm|title=Dolberg verwerft zich plek in de recordboeken|publisher=AFC Ajax|language=Dutch|date=20 November 2016}}</ref> On 9 March 2017, Dolberg scored the equalizer in what ended in a 2\u20131 loss to [[F.C. Copenhagen]] in the round of 16 of the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Europa League]] campaign, thus ending a club record eight-month period in which Copenhagen had not conceded any goals at their home ground at [[Parken Stadium]] since 20 August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajaxshowtime.com/article/hoofdnieuws/103028/dolberg-ik-weet-niet-wat-ik-verkeerd-deed|title=Dolberg: 'Ik weet niet wat ik verkeerd deed'|publisher=AjaxShowtime|language=Dutch|date=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===OGC Nice===\nDolberg signed for Nice on 29 August 2019 for a fee of 20.5 million Euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajax.nl/streams/actueel/officieel-kasper-dolberg-naar-ogc-nice.htm|title=OFFICIEEL: Kasper Dolberg naar OGC Nice|publisher=AFC Ajax|language=Dutch|date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn November 2016, Dolberg received his first call-up to the senior [[Denmark national football team|Denmark squad]] for matches against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] and [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.b.dk/sport/hareide-tager-teenagekomet-med-paa-landsholdet |title=Hareide tager teenagekomet med p\u00e5 landsholdet |publisher=b.dk |language=Danish |date=4 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref> On 11 November 2016, he made his senior international debut, coming on as a second-half substitute in a 4\u20131 victory for Denmark over Kazakhstan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dbu.dk/nyheder/2016/november/dan_kas_4-1 |title=Eriksen sprudleri dansk 4\u20131 sejr |publisher=dbu.dk |language=Danish |date=11 November 2016 |accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> On 10 June 2017, in a 1\u20133 away win against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers for the 2018 World Cup]], he came on as a substitute for [[Yussuf Poulsen]] after 68 minutes and scored his first international goal in the 81st minute.<ref>{{cite news|last1=W|first1=Christian|title=Very nice! Danes get past Kazakhstan in World Cup qualifier|url=http://cphpost.dk/news/very-nice-danes-get-past-kazakhstan-in-world-cup-qualifier.html|accessdate=10 June 2017|work=[[The Copenhagen Post]]|date=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 he was named in Denmark\u2019s preliminary 35-man [[Denmark national football team|squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad - 23-man & preliminary lists & when will they be announced?|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|website=Goal|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 16 September 2019, Dolberg reported to the police that his luxury watch at an estimated value of 70.000\u20ac was stolen. Following a police investigation, in which the police recovered a surveillance video showing the culprit stealing the watch, his teammate [[Lamine Diaby-Fadiga]] confessed to the crime ten days later.<ref name=\"Eurosport\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.fr/football/ligue-1/2018-2019/diaby-fadiga-reconnait-avoir-vole-la-montre-de-dolberg-dans-le-vestiaire_sto7475571/story-amp.shtml|title=Diaby Gadiga reconnait avoir vol\u00e9-la montre de Dolberg|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> Diaby was later sacked by the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49897317|title=Lamine Diaby-Fadiga sacked by Nice after stealing team-mate's watch|date=1 October 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|7 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Kasper Dolberg \u00bb Club matches|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/kasper-dolberg/2/|website=worldfootball.net|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"soccerway\">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/kasper-dolberg/316064/|title=Denmark - K. Dolberg - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway|publisher=soccerway.com|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=2|League\n!colspan=2|Cup{{efn|Includes [[Danish Cup]] and [[KNVB Cup]] matches}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Include [[Coupe de la Ligue]] matches}}\n!colspan=2|Europe{{efn|Includes [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]] matches}}\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n||[[Silkeborg IF]]||[[2014\u201315 Danish Superliga|2014\u201315]