sz genomineerd voor Rinus Michels Award|publisher=Ajaxshowtime.com|accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Dutch Footballer of the Year#Dutch Football Talent of the Year .28Young player.29|Dutch Football Talent of the Year]]: 2016\u201317<ref>{{cite web|title=Dolberg named Eredivisie talent of the year|url=http://www.football-oranje.com/dolberg-named-eredivisie-talent-year/|publisher=football-oranje.com|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Instagram|kasperdolberg}}\n*{{NFT|65838}}\n*[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/7268 Kasper Dolberg] at the [[Danish Football Association]]\n\n{{OGC Nice squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = Awards\n| bg          = Gold\n| bordercolor = #000000\n| list1       =\n{{Dutch Football Talent of the Year}}\n{{AFC Ajax Talent of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Denmark squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolberg, Kasper}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Silkeborg IF players]]\n[[Category:AFC Ajax players]]\n[[Category:OGC Nice players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:People from Silkeborg]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kasper_Dolberg"}
{"title_page": "William D. Bradshaw", "text_new": "{{short description|Early western U.S. Pioneer.}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William D. Bradshaw\n| image              =\n| alt                =\n| caption            =\n| image_size         =\n| birth_name         = William David Bradshaw<ref name=\"Block1\">{{cite web |last1=Block |first1=Kathy |title=The Bradshaw Brothers and the Bradshaw Trail |url=http://apcrp.org/BLOCK_KATHY/BRADSHAW_TRAIL/Bradshaw_Trail_Mast.htm |website=American Pioneer and Cemetery Project |publisher=APCRP |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = 1826\n| birth_place        = [[Buncombe County, North Carolina|Buncombe County]],<br>[[North Carolina]], U.S.<ref>Bell, pp 306.</ref>\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1864|12|02|1826|mf=y}}\n| death_place        = [[La Paz County, Arizona]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = Throat slashed\n| burial_place       = [[La Paz, Arizona]], U.S.\n| burial_coordinates =\n| monuments          =\n| other_names        = ''Big Bill Bradshaw'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Renee |title=Explorers Cross Paths with Tribe; |agency=The Desert Sun |pages=33A,37A |publisher=USA Today Network |date=March 20, 2016}}</ref><br>''Bunk Bradshaw''<ref>Bell, pp 306.</ref>\n| nationality        = United States\n| occupation         =\n}}\n\n'''William David \"Bill\" Bradshaw''' (1826\u20131864), was a [[United States]] western pioneer and prospector.  He is best remembered for forging the [[Bradshaw Trail]] from [[San Bernardino, California]] to [[La Paz, Arizona|La Paz]], in the [[New Mexico Territory]], in 1862<ref>La Paz became part of the [[Arizona Territory]] in 1863, and later the state of [[Arizona]].</ref>.  Initially this gave the populated areas of California's west coast a more direct route to the [[Steamboats of the Colorado River#Colorado River Gold Rush|Colorado River Gold Rush]] fields, but more importantly the trail opened up the [[Southern California]] [[Colorado Desert]] region, and beyond, to settlement and development.<ref>Johnston, pp 7-8.</ref>  \n\nAs part of the trail, and in partnership with William Warringer, on June 16, 1862, Bradshaw set up a ferry service to cross the Colorado River.  The ferry transported travelers across the river from a location called Providence Point in California, to La Paz in the New Mexico territory.<ref>Gunther, pp 407.</ref>\n\nBradshaw died in La Paz on December 2, 1864, after his throat was slashed with a [[drawknife]].<ref name=\"Block1\" />  Newspaper reports at the time stated Bradshaw had committed suicide.<ref>{{cite news |title=Private Letters from Arizona ... |agency=Petaluma Journal and Argus |volume=X |issue= 46 |page= 1 |publisher=McNabb & Cassidy |date=December 29, 1864}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=From Prescott Courier |agency=Holbrook Argus, Holbrook Arizona |volume= 1|issue= 5 |page= 4 |date=January 9, 1896}}</ref>  Given the nature of his death, and no witnesses, historians, such as Francis J. Johnston, think it likely he was murdered.<ref>Johnston, pp 79-82.</ref>\n\n==Places named for the Bradshaw brothers==\nTraditionally, it has been assumed that the following places were named in recognition of William Bradshaw.  Some historians have proposed that Bradshaw City, and the Bradshaw Mountains, were named for Isaac \"Ike\" Bradshaw, William's brother.  [[Roscoe G. Willson]] laid out his argument in favor of Isaac in the ''Arizona Republic'' in 1956<ref>{{cite news |last1=Willson |first1=Roscoe G. |title=The Case of the Bradshaw Mountains: Or, Which Brother Gave His Name? |agency=Arizona Republic |date=September 30, 1956 |location=Phoenix, Arizona |pages=112-113}}</ref>, and again in 1969.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Willson |first1=Roscoe G. |title=Ike or Bill ... Take Your Choice |agency=Arizona Republic |date=November 9, 1969 |location=Phoenix, Arizona |pages=48-49}}</ref>\n\n* [[Bradshaw City, Arizona]]<ref name=Find1>{{cite web |title=Bradshaw City Cemetery |url=https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/56979/bradshaw-city-cemetery |website=Find-A-Grave.com |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Bradshaw City Cemetery<ref name=\"Find1\" />\n* [[Bradshaw's Ferry]]\n* [[Bradshaw Mountains]]\n** [[Bradshaw Mountain High School]]\n** [[Humboldt Unified School District|Bradshaw Mountain Middle School]]\n** [[Bradshaw Mountain Railroad]]\n* Bradshaw Spring\n* [[Bradshaw Trail]]\n\n== References ==\n===Bibliography===\n* Bell, Major Horace, (1881). ''Reminiscences of a Ranger, or Early Times in Southern California'', Yarnell, Caystyle, & Mathers, printers.\n* Gunther, Jane Davies (1984). ''Riverside County, California, Place Names; Their Origins and Their Stories'', Riverside, CA. {{LCCN|8472920}}.\n* Johnston, Francis J (1987, revised from 1977). ''The Bradshaw Trail'', Historical Commission Press, Riverside, California.\n\n===Citations and notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradshaw, William David}}\n[[Category:Arizona pioneers]]\n[[Category:California pioneers]]\n[[Category:People from Buncombe County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1864 deaths]]\n\n{{US-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Early western U.S. Pioneer.}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William D. Bradshaw\n| image              =\n| alt                =\n| caption            =\n| image_size         =\n| birth_name         = William David Bradshaw<ref name=\"Block1\">{{cite web |last1=Block |first1=Kathy |title=The Bradshaw Brothers and the Bradshaw Trail |url=http://apcrp.org/BLOCK_KATHY/BRADSHAW_TRAIL/Bradshaw_Trail_Mast.htm |website=American Pioneer and Cemetery Project |publisher=APCRP |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = 1826\n| birth_place        = [[Buncombe County, North Carolina|Buncombe County]],<br>[[North Carolina]], U.S.<ref>Bell, pp 306.</ref>\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1864|12|02|1826|mf=y}}\n| death_place        = [[La Paz County, Arizona]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = Throat slashed\n| burial_place       = [[La Paz, Arizona]], U.S.\n| burial_coordinates =\n| monuments          =\n| other_names        = ''Big Bill Bradshaw'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Renee |title=Explorers Cross Paths with Tribe; |agency=The Desert Sun |pages=33A,37A |publisher=USA Today Network |date=March 20, 2016}}</ref><br>''Bunk Bradshaw''<ref>Bell, pp 306.</ref>\n| nationality        = United States\n| occupation         =\n}}\n\n'''William David \"Bill\" Bradshaw''' (1826\u20131864), was a [[United States]] western pioneer and prospector.  He is best remembered for forging the [[Bradshaw Trail]] from [[San Bernardino, California]] to [[La Paz, Arizona|La Paz]], in the [[New Mexico Territory]], in 1862<ref>La Paz became part of the [[Arizona Territory]] in 1863, and later the state of [[Arizona]].</ref>.  Initially this gave the populated areas of California's west coast a more direct route to the [[Steamboats of the Colorado River#Colorado River Gold Rush|Colorado River Gold Rush]] fields, but more importantly the trail opened up the [[Southern California]] [[Colorado Desert]] region, and beyond, to settlement and development.<ref>Johnston, pp 7-8.</ref>  \n\nAs part of the trail, and in partnership with William Warringer, on June 16, 1862, Bradshaw set up a ferry service to cross the Colorado River.  The ferry transported travelers across the river from a location called Providence Point in California, to La Paz in the New Mexico territory.<ref>Gunther, pp 407.</ref>\n\nBradshaw died in La Paz on December 2, 1864, after his throat was slashed with a [[drawknife]].<ref name=\"Block1\" />  Newspaper reports at the time stated Bradshaw had committed suicide.<ref>{{cite news |title=Private Letters from Arizona ... |agency=Petaluma Journal and Argus |volume=X |issue= 46 |page= 1 |publisher=McNabb & Cassidy |date=December 29, 1864}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=From Prescott Courier |agency=Holbrook Argus, Holbrook Arizona |volume= 1|issue= 5 |page= 4 |date=January 9, 1896}}</ref>  Given the nature of his death, and no witnesses, historians, such as Francis J. Johnston, think it likely he was murdered.<ref>Johnston, pp 79-82.</ref>\n\n==Places named for the Bradshaw brothers==\nTraditionally, it has been assumed that the following places were named in recognition of William Bradshaw.  Some historians have proposed that Bradshaw City, and the Bradshaw Mountains, were named for Isaac \"Ike\" Bradshaw, William's brother.  [[Roscoe G. Willson]] laid out his argument in favor of Isaac in the ''Arizona Republic'' in 1956<ref>{{cite news |last1=Willson |first1=Roscoe G. |title=The Case of the Bradshaw Mountains: Or, Which Brother Gave His Name? |agency=Arizona Republic |date=September 30, 1956 |location=Phoenix, Arizona |pages=112-113}}</ref>, and again in 1969.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Willson |first1=Roscoe G. |title=Ike or Bill ... Take Your Choice |agency=Arizona Republic |date=November 9, 1969 |location=Phoenix, Arizona |pages=48-49}}</ref>\n\n* [[Bradshaw City, Arizona]]<ref name=Find1>{{cite web |title=Bradshaw City Cemetery |url=https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/56979/bradshaw-city-cemetery |website=Find-A-Grave.com |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Bradshaw City Cemetery<ref name=\"Find1\" />\n* [[Bradshaw's Ferry]]\n* [[Bradshaw Mountains]]\n** [[Bradshaw Mountain High School]]\n** [[Humboldt Unified School District|Bradshaw Mountain Middle School]]\n** [[Bradshaw Mountain Railroad]]\n* Bradshaw Spring\n* [[Bradshaw Trail]]\n\n== References ==\n===Bibliography===\n* Bell, Major Horace, (1881). ''Reminiscences of a Ranger, or Early Times in Southern California'', Yarnell, Caystyle, & Mathers, printers.\n* Gunther, Jane Davies (1984). ''Riverside County, California, Place Names; Their Origins and Their Stories'', Riverside, CA. {{LCCN|8472920}}.\n* Johnston, Francis J (1987, revised from 1977). ''The Bradshaw Trail'', Historical Commission Press, Riverside, California.\n\n===Citations and notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradshaw, William David}}\n[[Category:American pioneers]]\n[[Category:People from Buncombe County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1864 deaths]]\n\n{{US-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "OvertAnalyzer", "label": "safe", "comment": "Revised Cat.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_D._Bradshaw"}
